[0m  [2m=== Root Cause Analysis ===
[0m  [2m
[0m  [2mBUG 1 — Duplicate Processing (Root Cause):
[0m  [2m  The `dequeue()` method's `await asyncio.sleep(0.01)` sits BETWEEN 
[0m  [2m  marking the job as "processing" and returning it. While the status 
[0m  [2m  IS set before yielding, the yield point creates unnecessary risk.
[0m  [2m  
[0m  [2m  More critically: `dequeue()` returns a LIVE REFERENCE to the job 
[0m  [2m  dict. When `fail()` sets status to "pending" (retry), the same 
[0m  [2m  worker's while loop IMMEDIATELY re-picks the job. Each retry 
[0m  [2m  re-executes the full processing including side effects.
[0m  [2m  
[0m  [2m  With max_retries=2, a bad job fires 3 times. If the convention
[0m  [2m  should be "max_retries=2 = at most 2 total attempts" not 
[0m  [2m  "2 retries + 1 original", this is the gap.
[0m  [2m
[0m  [2mBUG 2 — Vanishing Failures (Root Cause):
[0m  [2m  `await queue.dequeue()` and `print(...)` are OUTSIDE the try/except 
[0m  [2m  block in `process_job()`. If either raises (notably asyncio.
[0m  [2m  CancelledError when asyncio.gather cancels sibling workers, or 
[0m  [2m  any BaseException), the worker dies WITHOUT calling fail().
[0m  [2m  
[0m  [2m  The job remains "processing" forever — never "failed", never 
[0m  [2m  retried. It simply disappears from the queue.
[0m  [2m  
[0m  [2m  Additionally, if queue.fail() or queue.complete() itself raises 
[0m  [2m  (e.g., KeyError from corrupted _jobs), that exception propagates 
[0m  [2m  OUT of the except block, killing the worker.
